# Server Actions — Required Patterns

## File header
Every server action file must start with `'use server'` as the first line.

## Supabase client selection
Use the correct client for the context — never mix them:

| Client | When to use | Import |
|--------|-------------|--------|
| `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server` | Any action that reads session/auth (user-facing) | `import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/server'` |
| Service role client | Admin-only operations, cron jobs, background tasks | `createClient(url, process.env.SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY)` from `@supabase/supabase-js` |
| Anon client | Public read-only queries with no user context | `createClient(url, process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY)` from `@supabase/supabase-js` |

Never expose `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` to the client. Service role clients are server-only.

## Return shape
Return a typed result — never throw raw errors to the client:

```ts
// CORRECT
export async function doThing(): Promise<{ data: Foo | null; error: string | null }> {
  try {
    const result = await ...
    return { data: result, error: null }
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('[doThing]', err)
    return { data: null, error: 'Something went wrong' }
  }
}

// WRONG — throws expose stack traces and crash the UI
export async function doThing() {
  const result = await ... // throws on failure
  return result
}
```

## Null-guard env vars
Always check env vars before using them. Return null/error if missing:

```ts
function getServiceSupabase() {
  const url = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL
  const key = process.env.SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY
  if (!url?.trim() || !key?.trim()) return null
  return createClient(url, key)
}
```

## Naming conventions
- Files: `app/actions/{domain}.ts` (e.g. `listings.ts`, `auth.ts`, `brokers.ts`)
- Functions: `camelCase`, verb-first (e.g. `getListings`, `saveListing`, `deleteBanner`)
- Export types alongside actions in the same file

## Do NOT
- Import server actions into client components directly — use them via `useTransition` / `startTransition` or form `action=`
- Use `fetch()` inside server actions to call your own API routes — call the action function directly
- Put business logic in API routes when it belongs in a server action
